default&#xa0;defaultQ: defaultWhat is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to adefault local level decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGA does not accept that there has been a genuine devolution of decision making on transport to a 
defaultlocal level.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGA 
defaultwas
default pleased 
defaultto see the Government
default explicitly acknowledging that "local authorities have a crucial role to play in supporting housing and wider economic growth"
default, during 
defaultthe June 
default2013 
defaultSpending Round
default.
default The Government’s 
defaultcomments were 
defaultprompted by
default Lord Heseltine’s report on local growth
default,
default 
defaultwhich
default called for 
defaultWhitehall departments 
defaultto
default devolve more of their funding because local partners know better how to in
defaultvest these funds to best effect
default,
default a position that the LGA has long advocated.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGA 
defaulta
defaultccepts
default this has been 
defaultaccompanied by moves to put more levers and funding related to growth into local hands, including 
defaultthe Local Growth Fund, 
defaultthe partial retention of business rates, devolution of the majority of EU structural and investment funds to LEPs 
defaultand the extension of the city deal model to all LEPs as ‘growth deals'.
default There are 
defaultalso 
defaultencouraging signs that the Highways Agency is willing to work with local partners
default,
default although it remains to be seen how this will work in practice as its route based strategies develop. C
defaultouncils and other local partners 
defaultare keen to co-produce plans and shape the 
defaultdecisions
default on the £15 billion spend identified for the Strategic Roads Network
default (SRN)
default,
default which will ha
defaultve major impact
defaults
default on local growth. It is not enough 
defaultfor councils 
defaultto be just consulted on plans after they have been developed.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, we believe that 
defaultsignificant hurdles remain in defaultplace, hindering defaultthe ability of local partners to madefaultximise thdefaulteir drive for economic growth.default 
defaultWhitehall departments 
defaultremain
default resistant to joining up
default their efforts
default and 
defaultreleasing control to a local level
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultR
defaultather than pooling and localising funds through a single pot
default,
default as the 
defaultHeseltine 
defaultReview recommended, a £2 
defaultbillion a year “Local Growth Fund” has been created, drawing primarily on coun
defaultcil
default,
default or already-devolved
default,
default funding.  
defaultThe local growth fund requires councils to engage, through LEPs, in a competitive bidding process with entries being judged by Whitehall. 
defaultThisdefault is not devolution and is a long way from Lord Heseltine’s vision.default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition to this dilution of the fundamental principle
default of devolution, the G
defaultovernment has now indicated that it intends to attach conditions to highways maintenance funding. 
defaultAs this mone
defaulty makes up 
defaulta
default 
defaultgreater
default 
defaultportion of the capital transport funding councils receive from central government than previously
default,
default the effect will be to reduce the ability of councils to decide for themselves how transport funding should be spent.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government’s 
defaultapproach has caused unnecessary complications
default,
default with funding that was already announced for delivery by Local Transport Boards now to be handed over to LEPs with an allocation process
default 
defaultdifferent from other streams within the fund. This has given rise to seve
defaultral concerns:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultOverall, the Government has taken a distorted approach to funding. Whitehall 
defaultboasts of the £15bn it plans to spend on 
defaultthe 2% of the network controlled by Highways Agency (carrying a third of all traffic) by 2021, while offering £13bn to maintain and improve the other 98% over the same period (which carries two thirds of all traffic).
default&#xa0;
defaultFinally, transport spending is not si
defaultmply about capital projects. The elements that make up an areas transport network do not exis
defaultt in isolation from one another. U
defaultnless councils are in a position to take a holistic view of transport, integrating transport policy into policies on growth, hous
defaulting, health and education, devolved decision making is not possible. For all the Government’s talk of localism, 
defaultmeasures to devolve power to councils in respect of traffic management, bus services and rail franchising have amounted to very little in practidefaultce.default&#xa0;
defaultIt is our view that it is only possible to achieve best value from investment in spending where transport can be seen as a whole and transport policy integrated with other policies. Transport is not an end in itself and its component modes do not exis
defaultt in isolation from one another. At
default the
default local level
default,
default only councils are in a position to deliver this holistic approach and the chief disadvantage of the 
defaultGovernment’s
default approach is that it leads to a piecemeal siloed transport policy that does not deliver bes
defaultt value.
