defaultQ: defaultDo local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport defaultschemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?default&#xa0;
defaultCouncils have shown that they are capable of delivering schemes and working in partnership with
default LEPs, other councils and other stakeholders
default, such as the Highway Agency. 
defaultFor example, 
defaultCornwall 
defaultCounty 
defaultCouncil 
defaulthas demonstrated that it could
default deliver the upgrade to the A30 road for £20 million less than the Highways Agency’s plans, a 25% reduction in costs. Council projects often have a much higher return, with more than a quarter achieving a benefit-to-co
defaultst ratio of 5:1, according to the National Audit Office. By contrast, schemes are considered to have ‘high’ value for money by the Department for Transport if they produce £2 of economic benefit for every £1 spent.
default  
default&#xa0;
defaultGovernment cuts to local budgets of 43
default per cent mean councils have had to make difficult decisions on resourcing delivery, but they are doing so in innovative ways, such as working in partnership and through finding innovative solutions. Further funding cuts would threaten councils’ ability to
default innovate.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGA believes there is no optimum body as one size does not fit all. The purpose and value of devolution is that it recognises and enables the right organisations and solutions to come together to tackle the challenges and take opportuniti
defaultes that are unique to that area. Rather than prescribing a particular body
default,
default the LGA 
defaultwould like
default to see devolution that produces place and needs specific
default outcomes,
default enabling councils to take the holistic view of transport outlined above.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government estim
defaultates that 
defaulttraffic on the local roads network will increase by 4default1.5 per cent between 2010 and 2040default.default defaultThis will put impossible stress on the road network in some areas, hampering growth and creating gridlock. The example of London shows that where local gover
defaultnment has a wide range of tools it can 
defaultdeliver reductions in traffic levels
default (a 7.8 per cent fall in car traffic 2003-10)
default. Yet the government refuses to equip councils outside London with similar powers. Unless this changes some of our towns and cities will
default grind to a halt in the next twenty years.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ: defaultWhat is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?default&#xa0;
defaultCouncils are already working together on sub-r
defaultegional basis,
default be it through Local Transport Boards, Local Enterprise Partnerships or other local transport bodies.  Councils recognise that major transport schemes often cross boundaries and have shown they can work together on such matters. It should be up to local pa
defaultrtners to decide how best they should organise themselves to deal with major schemes that cross their boundaries.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn many areas councils are coming together to form alliances to find solutions for major transport improvement schemes. Alliances such as the
default A14 Alliance and A47 Alliance demonstrate that councils can work together and pool funding to help lever in investment.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ: defaultHow effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments and national transport agencies?default&#xa0;
defaultCouncils ha
defaultve consistently identified the 
defaultHighways 
defaultA
defaultgency
default 
defaultand National Rail 
defaultas barrier
defaults
default to delivering local growth. The Government has followed up its pledge from its command paper, Action for Roads to reform and modernise the 
defaultHighways Agency
default by launching a consultat
defaultion on the 29th October. The Government has stated that it will “support a much greater local and regional stakeholder involvement in planning for the [strategic roads] network and help to inform our investment decisions for the next spending review”.
default&#xa0;
defaultWit
defaulth councils and LEPs now having a clearer mandate on growth, and
default the
default Highways Agency undergoing reform, this presents an ideal opportunity for a new level of trust, engagement and partnership-working between local government, LEPs and the Highways Agency. 
defaultT
defaulthe forthcoming reforms must result in dialogue between the Highways Agency and local government on the wider issue of economic growth, as opposed to the previously narrow focus on just roads.
default&#xa0;
defaultGrowth is a key local priority and the 
defaultSRN
default 
defaultmakes a vital 
defaultcontribution.
default 
defaultThis is why route based assessments need to be a genuine coproduction between local authorities and the Highways Agency and need to consider all modes of transport and the local road network.  Councils do not just want to be consulted on HA p
defaultlans; councils want co-production of plans.  
default&#xa0;
defaultInvestment in the 
defaultSRN
default 
defaultneeds to be coordinated with the Strategic Economic Plans produced by Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs), as well as existing City Deal agreements. The partnership between 
defaultthe Highways 
defaultAgency
default and councils should not be confined to the SRN alone
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the difficulties local authorities have experienced with Network Rail
default,
default councils will want to ensure both that lessons are learned and that account is taken of the crucial difference betwee
defaultn rail, where there is a clear ‘end’ to the network, and road where any division between the 
defaultSRN
default and local roads is in fact artificial.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe SRN should not be considered in isolation from the local roads network or from transport provision as a whole. For instance, roads policy should be considered alongside, and integrated with, rail policy. This reflects an underlying principle 
defaultrunning th
defaultrough the LGA’s campaign, 
defaultRewiring Public Services
default which argues for a joined up approach to infrastructure investment.
