defaultQ: defaultDo the current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streamsdefault compare with previous arrangements?default&#xa0;
defaultCurrent funding arrangements will deliver more money for some councils
default,
default who will also benefit from the fact that the 
defaultLocal Growth Fund (
defaultLGF
default)
default provides a more flexible approach to funding major schemes than was the case 
defaultpreviously.  However there has been insufficient devolution of funding and the increased capital budget does not make sufficient provision for highways maintenance.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe DfT originally proposed reforming the local majors funding by dividing the fund betwee
defaultn Local Transport Boards (LTBs). The LGA had argue 
defaultfor
default the funding to be devolved to councils who would then make their own partnerships for cross-boundary schemes. The shift from the DfT’s original proposals to LGF was a retrograde step in the sense that 
defaultit was a return to the idea of centrally judged bidding process.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultLGA has been
default successful in 
defaultputting its
default case to
default the Department for Transport (DfT) to provide more resources for
default 
defaulttransport to councils. The 2015/16 Spending Round,
default 
defaultannounced on the 26 
defaultJune, more than doubled local majors transport scheme funding
default 
defaultfrom £375 million per annum to £819 million per annum.
default However, as this money has been subsumed into the LGF, this increase will only benefit those councils that are successful in bidding for LG
defaultF funds
default,
default and we have outlined above a number of concerns over how the LGF works. 
defaultNotwithstanding
default the
defaultse concerns, for those councils whose LGF bids are successful, the exercise offer
defaults
default a potentially significant opportunity to invest in local transport, but t
defaulthis success will be bought in part at the expense of those whose bids are not successful, and the wider success is spread (
defaulti.e.
default the greater the number of centrally approved bids), the less it is worth.
default Even for those councils who are successful, the cost o
defaultf bidding is substantial, particularly when local government is suffering 43% cuts (across the lifetime of the current Parliament).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe difficult position councils face
default,
default especially those not favoured by the judges of LGF bids, is compounded by persistent 
defaultshortcomings in the roads maintenance funding. 
defaultThe 
defaultincrease in highways maintenance funding in 
defaultthe 
default2010
default Spending
default 
defaultReview 
defaulthas, in effect, been achieved by cuts in the Integrated Transport Block (ITB)
default.
default For councils that receive no funding from the Local Growth Fund
default,
default the 
defaultcombined annual ITB and highways maintenance funding will be the same between the period 2015-21 as in 2014-5. 
defaultMoreover, as the 2013 ALARM survey
default estimated that current levels of govern
defaultment funding for roads maintenance in England fell short by £829m a year, it is obvious that the ‘increase’ will leave a considerable shortfall going forward and that further deterioration in the network will take place assuming recent levels of severe wea
defaultther damage continue. It would take ten years to repair the pothole backlog at current funding 
defaultlevels assuming no new ‘wear and tear’ was inflicted on our roads. However, the prospect of a 40 per cent increase in traffic as highlighted earlier suggests mai
defaultntenance pressures will increase in coming years. 
default&#xa0;
defaultMoreover, whilst capital funding has increased
default,
default councils are experiencing a rapid squeeze on vital revenue funding which is needed to develop and deliver quality 
defaultschemes. 
defaultThe 43default% reduction in core councildefault funding over the spending review period to 2015/16 will considerably restrict councils ability, not their willingness, to maximise the potential for their areas.default defaultWhere limited resources could be put to better use to develop high quality, value-for-money s
defaultchemes, councils 
defaulthave
default to devote time to reviewing governance arrangement from Local Transport Boards to LEPs, and competitive bidding for funds.
default&#xa0;
defaultFunding from a national perspective appears distorted.
default The G
defaultovernment boasts of the £15bn it plans to spend on
default the 2% of the network controlled by H
defaultighways 
defaultA
defaultgency
default (carrying a third of all traffic) by 2021, while offering £13bn to maintain and improve the other 98% over the same period (
defaultwhich carries
default two thirds of all traffic).
